  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 22:66-71",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Morning trial",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the proceedings of which, as reported by Lk., correspond to those of the night meeting reported by Mt. and Mk. (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 26:59-66",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 14:55-64",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), only much abridged. No mention of the attempt to get, through witnesses, matter for an accusation, or of the testimony concerning the word about destroying the temple. The Messiah question is alone noticed. Perhaps Lk. omitted the former because of their futility, though they were important as revealing the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "animus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the judges.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "66-71",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The third Jewish Trial.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "66",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "p",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "66",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "as soon as it was day",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The Oral Law decided that the Sanhedrin could only meet by daylight.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "elders of the people",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "“the presbytery",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the people,” as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 22:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "elders...chief priests...scribes",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 15:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The three constituent parts of the Sanhedrin, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Ma 14:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Sanhedrin was the successor of the Great Synagogue, which ended with Simon the Just. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Where",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " they met is uncertain. It was either in the Paved Hall, or ‘Hall of Squares’ ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "(Lisehath haggazzith)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; or in the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Beth Midrash",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Temple Synagogue), a chamber which abutted on the “middle wall of partition” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "(Chet),",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or in the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Chanujoth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ‘shops’ or ‘booths’ founded by the house of Hanan to sell doves, &c. for the temple.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "their council",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "]",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": " Synedrion",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", from which the word Sanhedrin (mistakenly spelt ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Sanhedrim)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is derived. The word is first found on the occasion when they summoned before them Hyrcanus II., son of Alexander Jannaeus. It gloried in being a mild tribunal, but was now an extremely degenerate body, and unworthy of its earlier traditions (Jos. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Antt.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " xiii. 10, § 6; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "B. J.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ii. 8, § 14). The Jewish authorities had lost the power of inflicting death; they could only pass sentence of excommunication, and hand over to the secular arm.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
